  "target_response": {
    "text": "HRV is heart rate variability — the small differences in timing between one heartbeat and the next. Counterintuitively, more variability is generally the better sign: it reflects how recovered your nervous system is, and it's read against your own baseline rather than a universal number. I can't tell you yours, though. Your setup is manual logging, which gives me sleep and workout entries but no heart data at all — last night's 6.7 hours of sleep is the only measurement I have today. Reading HRV takes a sensor worn overnight, usually a chest strap, ring, or watch. If you add one, a few weeks of readings would establish your personal baseline and make the number worth watching.",
